Introduction:

This documentation is for those, who always wanted to know how the effects
in different formats are played. But unfortunatly no Player or Tracker has
a really 'good' documentation of them. So, take a look into this list for
more infos about them. For those whom don't write a player or get bored,
stop it ! It's only for them who want to know them exact.
This is very important to gain full compatibel to the formats and if there
are any errors or you think there is something wrong, tell me ! But first
try it out on the given tracker and if there is REAL an error, give me also
an example, please ! It is hard to find out on my self on which
circumstandes it will appear.

I tested many hours on the trackers and my player so EVERY effects was tested
first if it was played right !

<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>

(I)

Following formats are inplemented in F/X Player now:

  Name                         Shortcut            Player used for testing

- Scream Tracker 3.xx           (S3M)               Scream Tracker 3.2
(- Pro Tracker                   (MOD)               - none - )
(- Impuls Tracker 2.xx           (IT)                Impuls Tracker 2.12 )
(- Fast Tracker 2.xx             (XM)                Fast Tracker 2.06 )

For every format several test are archieved in given player version so all
effects explained are tested on that version and is implemented this way
in F/X Player too !



(II) Formats explaining


 Scream Tracker 3.xx
---------------------------------------------

This format is the first coded in F/X Player and is very well tested.
Not all effects are 100% compatible coz some seems to be a 'bug' so they are
changed in F/X but this is told then.

Some general informations:

A S3M channel is build in the following way:

  Note+Octave, Instrument, Volume, Effect & effect value

for example:   > |C-4 01  64  A06|

This means start a new instrument Nr. 01 at Note C of octave 4 with 64
volume and set speed to 06 frames per row.

The special commands (effects) are saved by it's character Number.
This means A = 01, B = 02 .... T = 20 etc. A value of 255 means empty
effect / not used. Values of 0 are in some cases not legal.


Here are now the effects and some commends which I thought are worth to talk
about it:

> Axx -- Set speed to xx

  This command is, like in all formats I know so far, to set the number of
  frames to move one row forward. This means, after xx frames are encountered
  a new row beginns, e.g. move one row forward. The length of one frame is
  selected by the Txx command, where a frame will be explained more clearly.
  If xx = 0 then it will be ignored.

  ATTENTION: The priority is from left to right !

  By the way, 'frame' and 'tick' are the same !! It is a different terminology
  of the same thing ! So don't get confused by reading both in this doc :)


> Bxx -- Jump to order xx

  This effect does exact that what it's said. It jumps after playing this row
  to the end, to the given pattern in the choosed order. So if the order is:

   01 -> 01
   02 -> 02
   03 -> 04

  and a B03 is encountered in pattern 2 (order 2) it jumps to pattern Nr. 4
  (order 3 !) and starts from the beginning (row 0).

  ATTENTION: The priority is from right to left !


> Cxx -- Break pattern to row xx

  Some mod-like command which come also from the AMIGA :)
  After playing this row to the end, it jumps into the next pattern of the
  given order (exact: it jump into next order) and starts there in row xx.

  ATTENTION: The priority is from right to left !

  ATTENTION !
  The xx data is internally in the S3M pattern saved as a BCD number !!!!
  This means C42 is NOT 42h (hex) it is 42d (dezimal) !!


> Dxy -- Volume Slides by xy

  This effects must be divided into several different:

  - D0y -- normal Volume slide down by y

    Every non-row-frame (e.g. all ticks exept the first of a new row)
    the volume is subtracted by y and all values beyond 0 are clipped to 0

  - Dx0 -- normal Volume slide up by x

    Every non-row-frame the volume is raised by x and values above 64 are
    clipped.

  - DFy -- Fine Volume slide down by y

    Only on the row-frame (e.g. only the first frame of a new row) volume is
    lowered by y, values below 0 are clipped.

  - DxF -- Fine Volume slide up by x

    On row-frame volume is raised by x and values over 64 are clipped to 64.

  - D0F -- Fine + Normal Volume slide down

    A very special volume slide which is wrong documentated in Scream Tracker.
    It is said, this acts like a normal volume slide with the value 15 (=0Fh)
    but it acts like a fine volume slide AND a normal too ! So the volume is
    changed EVERY frame, not only all non-row-ticks ! Clipped as usual...

  - DF0 -- Fine + Normal Volume slide up

    The same as above, only with sliding up.

  - DFF -- treated as fine volume slide up by F (=15)

    Treated like a normal fine volume slide up by 15.


> Exx -- Slide down by xx

  - E00 - EDF -- Normal slide down

    This is easy explained. Every non-row-frame the actual periode playing
    is added by xx * 4. This periode must of cause recalculated to the
    frequence of this new periode.

  - EFx -- Fine slide down by x

    In this row-frame periode is added by x * 4. Then calculate frequence
    etc.
    Give attention that this will only ONCE added during the row-frame like
    a fine volume slide.

  - EEx -- Extra fine slide down by x

    Like file slide but x is not multiplied.


> Fxx -- Slide up by xx

  - F00 - FDF -- Normal slide up

    The same as Normal slide down only this time you must subtract the
    periode

  - FFx -- Fine slide up by x

    Same as fine slide down.

  - FEx -- Extra fine slide up by x

    Guess what :)


> Gxx -- Tone portamento by xx

  This is one of the complicatest but also one of the most powerfull effects
  used. This command is for sliding to a specific note given so it is a kind
  of slide up/down but it is stopped if the note is reached.


> Hxy -- Vibrato with speed x and depth y

  This command is one of the most used but in comparison to the other commands
  it acts some different as normal. First, it does not take the old value
  of the last command if an H00 is encountered but it use the last value of
  the last Vibrato command. This means, if you encounter a H34, then next row
  a E12 and then a H00, the 34 of the old vibrato will be used. So it has
  its own memory to save its values. Another unusuall behavior is, if x = 0
  but y <> 0, x = the x value of the last vibrato command. If y = 0 and
  x <> 0 the vibrato will be played but as the amplitude is multiplied by y,
  you will hear the normal note and no vibrato.

  But now to the Vibrato itself. The x value is for the speed (x = 0 is not
  allowed) and gives the steplength for the sinetable (or ramp or ...).
  The y value is for the amplication of the vibrato and says how "strong" the
  vibrato will sound. So if y is zero there is no changing of the tone but
  the vibrato is running.
  If after a vibrato is an other command (besides of fine vibrato) the tone
  jumps back to the origin tone from what the vibrato started.
  BUT there is one exeption ! If the following command (with no space between)
  is Exx or Fxx (the both slide commands) then the tone will not jump back but
  the actuall playing tone will be slided up or down, just like a normal tone
  sliding.


> Ixy -- Tremor with ontime x and offtime y


> Jxy -- Arpeggio; adds halfnotes 0,x,y

  This effect is well known on the good old C64 to make chords with only
  one channel. Arpeggio plays first the last note, then adds x halfnotes
  on the orginal note, then y halfnotes, and this cycles through every frame
  so that all 3 frames it starts from the beginning.
  Attention: It does not remember at which notes it stops last row so every
             new row it starts from the beginning again, so at a speed of 2
             (2 frames every row) the third note (note+y) was never played :(
             Also is the last note the REAL last note given and no slided
             tone like after a slide or glissando command.
             And third, the last arpeggio tone is hold if a effect follows
             exept of a Dxx (volume slide) command.


> Kxy -- Dual command: H00 & Dxy


> Lxy -- Dual command: G00 & Dxy


> Mxx -- Not used !


> Nxx -- Not used !


> Oxx -- Set sample offset to xx00h

  Very usfull if you want to start a sample not just at the beginning but
  everywhere in the sample, quite usefull to make techno effects or for
  making a hihat out of a snare.
  So the xx is multiplied by 256 and this is not the 'real' offset of the
  sample but it is the number of samples where the playback will start.
  Or other said, if the sample is a 8bit mono it is the offset but for a
  16bit mono it must be multiplied by 2 or for a 16bit stereo by 4 and so
  on. This effect will only work with combination of a note.
  But in difference written in the S3M documentation there is no loop
  rewarp eg. if the sample is looped and the offset is greater then the
  loopend it will be not calculated like the loop is taken but it is set to
  given adress like an unlooped sample or in worst case over the end of
  sample so the sample playback is stopped immediatly.


> Pxx -- Not used !


> Qxy -- Retrig Note, x = Volumechange and y = frame count

  A retrig is basically to restart the sample from the beginning again.
  This means the offset of the sample would set to 0 and the LAST pitch
  (so the last pitch even after a slide or so) would be played.
  After y frames (row frame not counted) the sample will be restarted again
  and after y frames retrig again and so on. So by a speed of 7 and a y value
  of 3 it will be played 2 times. (row frame not counted, two frames empty,
  next frame retrig, two frames empty, retrig = 7 frames = speed 7 )
  BUT at a speed of 6 it will only retirg ONCE ( row frame, two frames empty,
  retrig, two empty = 6 frames, the 7th frame would be the next retrig !)
  so the first frame of the next row would be the retrig frame and this WILL
  happen if the next effect is a retrig too. So it is as all frames of the
  retrig-rows will be counted as one big row but if only one row will be no
  retrig, the frame counter will start from 0 (with the row frame not counted)

  But this is only the first half what the retrig command does.
  The x value is for changing the volume every time a retrig happens.
  There are 16 possabilities for changing the volume:

   0:    0        4:   -8        8:    0        C:    8
   1:   -1        5:  -16        9:    1        D:   16
   2:   -2        6: *2/3        A:    2        E: *3/2
   3:   -4        7: *1/2        B:    4        F:   *2

 Ok, these are the official values, but ST3 don't take them always exact.
 All volumes are rounded down (cut fraction) and volumes over 64 are skipped
 to 64 and volumes under 0 are set to 0 (like volumslides).
 Then value 6, 2/3 should be about 0.666... but ST3 multiplies the volume
 by 0.625, ok, F/X takes the 0.625. The other volumes are calculated like
 in the table listed above.


> Rxy -- Tremolo with speed x and depth y


> Sxy -- Special effects

  This is divided into following cases:

  - S0x
  - S1x
  - S2x
  - S3x
  - S4x
  - S8x -- Set pan position

    Well, very easy to implement, the value sets direct the panning with
    0 = full left, F = full right and 7 = middle. The other values are
    pannings between those.

  - SAx -- old 'Set pan position'

    This is the mystic panning command of the old ST 3.0 which was only used
    in the Panic trackmo from Future Crew. It contains 8 different panning
    stats with :
                  0 = L        = equal with pan ?
                  1 = R        =                ?
                  2 = LL       =                ?
                  3 = RR       =                ?
                  4 = LL - R   =                ?
                  5 = L - RR   =                ?
                  6 = L - R    =                ?
                  7 = LL - RR  =                ?

  - SBx -- Pattern loop

    This is some outdated but still in use so I will explain it here.
    With this command you can repeat a serpent number of rows in the actuall
    pattern playing. The command is devided in two kinds, the start marker
    and the repeat counter. The start marker is set if you set x to 0, so
    it will go back to the row last time this marker was set.
    For default this marker is set to row 0 every time a new pattern is
    encountered.
    If x is set to a value from 1 to 0Fh is this the counter how many times
    it will jump back to the last start marker position, so with value 2
    it will jump back 2 times, so the rows between are played three times
    (once played normally and twice played coz of backjump) so you can
    compare it to a DO/WHILE loop ;)
    If all the loop is played the start marker will automatically set to the
    next row after the repeat marker.

  - SCx -- Note cut in x frames

    Hm, one sentence: After x frames the sample in this channel is stopped,
    like a 'key off' but with a frame counter.
    BUT: x greater as the speed are ignored (logic: how can it stop a sample
         at a given frame if that frame does not exist !)

  - SDx -- Note delay for x frames

    This is for delaying the begin of a new note, instrument and also volume.
    It would be treated as if the note, instrument and volume does not exist
    in the row and the old sample and volume is played like nothing happend
    but ONLY since x frames are gone, then the new note, instrument or volume
    (or all together) starts and overwrite the old values.
    => x greater then speed: the same as under 'Note cut'.

  - SEx -- Pattern delay for x rows

    Very easy to explain but not so easy to implement. The x tells us how
    many times this line would be played (all channels !!) like if that row
    would be standing x times after each other but with one BIG difference:
    Only the effects are played again. Notes, instrument or volume values
    are ignored during that repeating. So better said : only the effects
    are copied x times after each other.

    ATTENTION: Priority from left to right !


> Txx -- Tempo=xx (21h - FFh)

  Well, this command is to set the tempo on which now the song is played.
  The number xx gives the BPM (Beats per Minute) on which it will be played.
  Actually this says how 'long' one frame will be. It is calculated by
  following formula:

    frame length = (Mixing Speed * 5) / (tempo * 2)

  This value tells you now how many samples (bytes/words) must be calculated
  to do ONE frame.
  So at a Mixing Speed of 44100 Hz and a tempo of 125 (7Dh) it is:

   (44100 * 5) / (125 * 2) = 882

  So there are 882 samples calculated per channel to move one frame forward.
  Every frame the effects were executed as needed and volume, pitch etc
  will be updated. After by the Axx command set frames (xx= number of frames)
  you have to move one row forward and read notes, volumes etc. again.
  This means practically for example to do a volume slide down by 2 (D02)
  and a speed of 6:

  |C-4 01  64  D02|  - first frame of row note, instrument and volume is read
           62        - second frame (non-row-frame) sub volume by 2
           60        - again
           58        - etc.
           56          ...
           54        - last frame (Nr. 6) lower volume by 2
  |--- --  --  D02|  - next row only a volumslide appears but do not execute
           52        - lower volume by 2 again
           50          ...
           ...

  Values less then 21h will be ignored as like there was no Txx command.
  Tho, the meaning of frames and non-row-frames is hopefully clear now.


> Uxy -- Fine Vibrato with speed x and depth y

  The same like Hxy (Vibrato) only 4 times finer (1/4 so deep). This is for
  high notes playing where a normal Vibrato sounds too strong. So this finer
  Vibrato is used.


> Vxx -- Set global volume (0 - 40h)

  This commands set the global volume which effects ALL channels. The valid
  range is from 0 to 64 (40h). The end volume for every channel is calculated
  by:

     End volume = (Global Volume * Channel Volume) / 64

  The divison by 64 is of course easier by shift it right 6 times.
  This calculation must be done for every channel. The use is for global
  lowering volume for end- or beginning of a S3M for example.
  But give attention that the new global volume will first take effect by
  a new note in every channel !

  ATTENTION: The priority is from right to left !


> Wxx -- Not used !


> Xxx -- unused amiga command 8xx :)

  If you load a MOD and save it as S3M, the 8xx command is saved as this Xxx.
  Besides, the 8xx command is used in DMP for panning.


> Yxx -- Not used !


> Zxx -- Not used !


NOT FINISHED YET !!

